7. cervam fugere etc. depend on adulescentulum videre. In Terence video is often followed by an Ins. with Ace. expressed or understood; sometimes by a Participle. as is the rule with Augustan writers. Cf. 177. We know nothing of the passage here alluded to, but we gather that the style of Lanuvinus was somewhat sensational and melodra- matie. 18. ab studio studuit. The juxtaposition of two words of the same root is common in Terence. This is merely a special form ofAssenance, and is to be distinguished from Agnominatiocr Pamnomasia, which, strictly speaking, is a play upon words of similar-sound but different sense. something akin to a pun, e. g. Andr. 218 inceptio est amentium haud amantium. paronomasia is fairly common in Plautus, but rare in Terence. The term is sometimes extended to a play upon different meanings of the same word, such as is not uncommon in Cicero, e. g. ius Verrinam. Cf. Dem. de Cor. 13.
